I am an associate professor of statistics at Pennsylvania State
University. I received my Ph.D. from
the <a href="http://www.stat.umn.edu"> School of Statistics</a> at the
University of Minnesota and a B.S. in <a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu">
Computer Science</a> (with minors in Statistics, Mathematics and Film)
from Carnegie Mellon University. I was a postdoctoral fellow at
the <a href="http://www.niss.org"> National Institute of Statistical
Sciences </a> (courtesy appointment at Duke University)
(2003--2004) </a> and a New Research Fellow at the Statistical and
Applied Mathematical Sciences
Institute <a href="http://www.samsi.info">(SAMSI) </a> program
(2009--2010) on space-time analysis. I spent my sabbatical
(2011--2012) at the <a href="http://www.stat.washington.edu/">
Department of Statistics</a>, University of Washington, Seattle. I
provide below a summary of my
 <a href="http://www.stat.psu.edu/~mharan/index.html#Research">
